    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_179939568" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/179939568" />
    <a title="aPriL does feral sometimes " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes"><img alt="aPriL does feral sometimes " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1478243665p2/3409532.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/179939568?book_show_action=true">Jun 26, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="aPriL does feral sometimes " class="user" itemprop="url" name="aPriL does feral sometimes " href="/user/show/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes">aPriL does feral sometimes </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/9814204-the-tiger-s-wife">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=literary">literary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3409532-april-does-feral-sometimes?shelf=metafiction">metafiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer179939568" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer490050890682032994">Despite a university education, medical degrees, and the kind-hearted motives of some of the main characters of &apos;The Tiger&apos;s Wife&apos; by Téa Obreht, a grandfather and granddaughter, and the scientifically proven science of healing, no one can stop destructive village myth-making behind local fears and grief caused by Death. Death cannot be simply a scientific process in the minds of locals, it has to have a physical presence and an intelligence, motivation and purpose. Death must be made into a phy</span>
  <span id="freeText490050890682032994" style="display:none">Despite a university education, medical degrees, and the kind-hearted motives of some of the main characters of 'The Tiger's Wife' by Téa Obreht, a grandfather and granddaughter, and the scientifically proven science of healing, no one can stop destructive village myth-making behind local fears and grief caused by Death. Death cannot be simply a scientific process in the minds of locals, it has to have a physical presence and an intelligence, motivation and purpose. Death must be made into a physical monster for people to grasp it. To villager eyes, Death's powers can be suborned by evil spirits bent on wrecking ordinary family life. Death is impossible to think about unless it is somehow mythologized into mystical human patterns, hard science be damned. Modern science in the form of serum inoculations against disease are no match for religious beliefs hundreds of years old. <br /><br />People create mystical mythologies out of sudden events that befuddle and frighten them. They must have a context which makes sense to their local folk sensibilities and understandings. The novel recreates a meta-story repeated over and over by ignorant villagers: the isolated village with expected roles for each villager in relationship to the village are reprised several times decades apart in the book. Outsiders who drift into a village's story become caught in a web of local suspicion. The villagers are not sure these newcomers aren't evil spirits rather than people no matter how long they stay. Fear compresses time and feelings into wild scapegoating and more superstitious explanations made to fit after hundreds of whispered consultations among neighbors. <br /><br />Then, further upset by the intrusion of a war and a tiger, impossible events to village thinking without some kind of magical evil having been drawn by an unknown disturbance to their misty isolated forest village, cause a panic. The villagers link stories in mythical terms about the appearance of the tiger to an outsider child wife of their brute of a butcher. To the villagers, a logical cause and effect. It's so sad. <br /><br />All of this past history shapes the childhood of a beloved grandfather who dies mysteriously far from home. His granddaughter, recipient and confidant of her grandfather's personal stories, feels the need to flesh out the stories of his past, to make of his death a meaningful death in her grief. <br /><br />I am someone who prefers the truth of science reality. This book reveals how the extreme human fear of meaningless death causes sad, to me, struggles of the mind for cause and effect in typical brain pathways throughout history. The interplay of community, the past and survival of the group means much more than individual truth or reality. The survival of the tribe especially under stresses like Death bring the most primitive coping mechanisms into action. <br /><br />As Obreht shows, love and fear twine together in an apparent psychological necessity for mystic explanations about death. These myths are preferred over demeaning reality and shameful human behaviors and stupidities. It is left to personal reader interpretation of the exposed mythological underbelly in 'The Tiger's Wife' of our psychological responses to death. I have a bad taste in my mouth from reading this book and seeing the mental twists people do to reject reality. Even brute animals are supposed by people as having a reason to consciously resort to devastating acts - stories which talk folks down from their high ledges of unbearable fear. Sigh. A very depressing book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="490050890682032994" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

