    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2849658190" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2849658190" />
    <a title="Joy D" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/50297885-joy-d"><img alt="Joy D" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1450639623p2/50297885.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2849658190?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joy D" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joy D" href="/user/show/50297885-joy-d">Joy D</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/20553093-the-tiger-s-wife">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=audio">audio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=war">war</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=europe">europe</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=fables-or-myths">fables-or-myths</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=storytelling">storytelling</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=family-dynamics">family-dynamics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=zck">zck</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/50297885-joy-d?shelf=magical-realism">magical-realism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2849658190" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17475177735859441613"><i>“Everything necessary to understand my grandfather lies between two stories: the story of the tiger&apos;s wife, and the story of the deathless man. These two stories run like secret rivers through all the other stories of his life--my grandfather&apos;s days in the army; his great love for my grandmother; the years he spent as a surgeon and a tyrant of the University. One, of which I learned after his death, is the story of how my grandfather became a man; the other, which he told to me, is of how he bec</i></span>
  <span id="freeText17475177735859441613" style="display:none"><i>“Everything necessary to understand my grandfather lies between two stories: the story of the tiger's wife, and the story of the deathless man. These two stories run like secret rivers through all the other stories of his life--my grandfather's days in the army; his great love for my grandmother; the years he spent as a surgeon and a tyrant of the University. One, of which I learned after his death, is the story of how my grandfather became a man; the other, which he told to me, is of how he became a child again.”</i><br /><br />Natalia is a medical professional living the region, not specifically named, of former Yugoslavia. Her grandfather has recently died, and she travels with a colleague to perform medical duties and retrieve her grandfather’s personal effects. She recalls memories of going to the zoo with her grandfather. His backstory includes two traditional folktales, the tale of the tiger’s wife the legend of the deathless man. The experiences of war form a key portion of the narrative – both WWII and the more recent Wars of Yugoslav Succession. While none of the specific locations is named, it is easy to figure out from the context.<br /><br />This book reads like a puzzle where the reader is searching for the interlocking pieces. I consider it an excellent example of literature assisting in intercultural understanding. I would not call it an easy read. It requires focused concentration and a careful examination of the pieces and parts in order to make sense of the whole. <br /><br />I enjoy Téa Obreht’s writing. I had recently read her second novel, <i>Inland,</i> and enjoyed it immensely, so decided to read another of her works. The two books are highly original and significantly different from each other. Taken together, these two works showcase her versatility as a writer. I look forward to reading her next offering. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17475177735859441613" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

